{"/service/ndnp/mohi/batch_mohi_linus_ver01/data/sn89066129/00294557209/1908011801/0443.xml":{"full_text":"1 took auaif(\ni\nTHE LACLEDE BLADE\nA. J. OAT WOOD, Editor and Publisher.\nin tared at the Laolede poatofflc tor\ntransmission through the mails as second\nel tas matter.\nSATURDAY, JAN. 18. 1908\nFROM THE NATIONAL CAPITOL\nOur Special Correspondent Writes Entertainingly\not Things at Washington.\nThe Question as to whether\nFrank H. Hitchcock, first assistant\npostmaster general, will or will not\nassume he management of the\npresidential interests of Secretary\nTaft has been cause for much dis\ncussion in political circles for\nweeks past. It has\nmost authoritatively\nMr. Hitchcock will\ndischarge his duties\npostmaster general\nfinally been\nstated that\ncontinue to\nas assistant\nwhile Mr\nthe manage\nVorys will continue\nment of Mr. Taft's political affairs.\nMr. Hitchcock, it is said, has not\nbeen asked up to the present time\nto command the Taft forces, and\nhas never considered the possibili\nty of resigning his present post as\nfirst assistant postmaster general, a\nplace he has filled to the entire sat\nisf action of the postmaster general\nand the administration. Most of\nthis ffossio has arisen from a call\non the secretary of war by Mr.\nHitchcock on the return of the for\nmer from the far East, a call\nprompted on the part of Mr.\nHitchcock by the gossip so assidu\nously spread abroad in Washington\nthat he, Mr. Hitchcock, was exert\ning such influence as he possessed\nto promote the political aspirations\nof Secretary Cortelyou, and which\nhe wished to deny personally to Mr\nTaft. He assured the secretary of\nhis entire loyalty and of his desire\nto do everything in his power, com\npatible with his duties in the post-\notilc& xlepartmen t, to promote the\ninterests of Mr. Taft.\nSenator Hale, chairman of the\ncommittee on naval affairs, has\ncreated a good deal of excitement\nand earnest comment and has fur\nnished the basis for a full and free\ndiscussion of navy matters by his\nbill \"to insure the efficiency of the\npersonnel of the navy and marine\ncorps of the United States.\" It is\nperfectly apparent that there will\nbe a complete airing of the trouble\ninvolving the naval administration,\nwith particular reference to the bu\nreau system, the construction ot\nships and the action of the presi\ndent in ordering that surgeons, in\nstead of line officers, shall be plac\ned in command of hospital ships.\nThe bill is looked upon as a direct\nslap to President Roosevelt for his\npart in the naval controversy, and,\nin a way, as a vindication of Ad\nmiral Brown son.\nSenator La Follette found him\nself between the devil and the\ndeep sea\" as a member of the com\nmittee on military affairs and so,\nbeing a man of great discretion.\nresigned his membership. It must\nbe recalled that Mr. La Follette has\npresidential aspirations and then it\nwill be readily understood that his\nposition was a truly delicate one\nas his vote, either pro or con, in\nthe Brownsville affair, would neces\nsarily alienate the friends of the\nopposite faction. It seems not to\nhave occurred to Mr. La Follettee\nthat he could have declined to vote\non the ground that he, as a recent\nmember of the committee, had not\nheard all the arguments in the case.\nThe episode is causing no little\namusement among certain members\nof the military affairs committee\nwho are not sorry to have this di\ndactic, pedantic member resign. He\nis anything bnt a favorite among\nhis collegues in Washington.\nConsiderable discussion and crit\nicism are heard of the Aldrich fi- j\nnancial bill, but the concensus of\nopinion is that, with some modifi\ncations, it will get through both\nhouses of congress in a reasonably\nshort time.\nThis has been a busy week at the\nnew house office building. Many\ncongressmen have gone through the\nbuilding selecting the rooms they\nwould like to occupy but, in most\ncases, will not, while many com\nmittees were moving in. The\nrooms on the west, south and east\nsides are habitable and have been\nfitted up for occupancy though the\nbuilding is not completed by any\nmeans. The occupants will have\neverything: conducive to comfort\nand convenience, and of air and\nlight there will be an abundance\nThe method of drawing for the\nrooms is similar to that used in the\ndistribution of seats in the house,\nand while all cannot get a room\non tne nrst noor, tney cannot De\nbut. pleased with their lot, wherever\ntheir luck places them.\nFormer Fourth Assistant Post\nmaster General J. L. Bristow is in\nWashington this week and declares\nit as his- opinion that Secretary\nTaft's chances for the nomination\nare growing orignter every aay,\nand that by the time the convention\nmeets in Chicago in June next, he\nwill be practically assured of the\nnomination. He says, further,\nSecretary Taft's Boston speech has\ndone him more good as a candidate\nthan any expression of any candi\ndate in the present campaign for\nthe republican nomination. It has\nshown the people that Secretary\nTaft has been as much a builder of\nthe policies of the administration as\nthe president himself, and his co\noperation with the president m\ncarrying out these policies has been\nalmost as important a factor in the\nsuccess of these policies as have the\nlabors of Mr. Roosevelt. Those\npersons who are predicting that\nMr. Taft's attitude toward labor,\nwill injure him know not whereof\nthey speak, and their statements\nreflect not their belief, but their\nwishes.\"\nTaft and Labor\nThe structure that has been rais\ned by the anti-Tafters out of the\nsecretary's attitude toward labor\nwhen he was a federal judge will\nprobably fall down. Heretofore\nbut one side has been heard, and\nthat was generally made up of mal\nicious misstatements. To 'get the\nmatter squarely before the country,\nthe Ohio Federation of Labor re\ncently addressed a series of questions\nto Mr. Taft, and his answers ought\nto set him straight with fair-minded\npeople.\nAs to what he would think of\n\"a provision that no restraining\norder or injunction should be issued\nexcept after notice is given to the\ndefendant and a hearing is had,\"\nMr. Taft replies that this was the\nold rule under the federal statutes,\nand that it could well be restored.\nAs to'whether he would approve\na law defining the cases in which\na temporary order may issue, and\ndefining in specific terms the lan\nguage in which such an order may\nI\nbe framed,\" he answers that he\nsees no objection to legislation de\nfining more exactly the rights of\nboth parties, and adds that \"the\nmore exactly the law or the limita\ntions on the actions of both parties\nare understood the better for them\nand for the public.\"\nWhat would he say to a proposal\nthat contempt proceedings under\nan injunction be heard by some\njudge other than the one who is-1\nsued the injunction itself f He be-i lt 18 such hideous, fantastic no\nlieves such a restriction would in t0113 honor as these that make\nmost cases be unnecessary, but that men oul an wmen base: Real\nit would not be unreasonable, and\nthat inasmuch as it would do away\nwith existing appearances of injus-!\ntice it would be desirable.\nThe position he assumes ought\nto satisfy the critics of these abuses,\nMr. Taf ts's speech at Cooper Union,\nin New York, on Friday night won\nthe approval of an immense aud-\nience. His topic was \"Capital and\nLabor\" certainly a delicate one for\na candidate for the presides, but\nhe handled it with a frankness and\nfairness that marks a big and cour-\nageous man, blessed with a charm-\nin or mnnndr nnrl infinite cVnnrl nil.\n\nDoom is growing daily are shutting\ntheir eyes to the facts.\nIn view of what is going for-\nward, it is difficult to grasp the\nnwriiAtimi mn hv RnnAtnr fifmiA\nYTr t li T V, i\nand Mr. Bryan that Mr. Cannon\nwill be the republican nominee,\nSenator Stone used to be regarded\nas a political 'prophet in Missouri,\n..i. i-i.-. iu. j u\nouu timt was m uio uaja wxicu y-\nbody could score by predicting that\nMissouri would go democratic. As\ntor uoionel J5ryan, he never was\neither a prophet or even a success\nful guesser. Speaker Cannon's\nchances hang on the ability of re-\npublican congressmen, whom he\nrules, to deliver Cannon delega\ntions to the republicanconvention,\nBut in the present frame' of the\npublic mind, this will be an exceed\ningly uphill job. The average\nAmerican voter, republican or\ndemocratic, is.a pretty independent\nchap nowadays, and the republican\ncongressman as a rule is very glad\nto hold his own. He doesn't drive\nhis constituents; he sails his craft\nas the wind blows from that quar-\nter. St. Joseph News-Press.\nHonor\nThere seems to be several kinds\nof honor if one can judge by the\nHarry Thaw.\nFor instance, young Mr. Thaw\nof Pittsburg and New York Recent\nly killed a fellow-being, and he did\nit in the name of honor. The vic-\ntim had dishonored -his wife, there-\nfore he must die. j\nA correspondent in a New York J\nnewspaper, discussing the Charac\nter of the victim of the tragedy,\nsaid he was \"the soul of honor.\"\nNo doubt he was in some respects. I\nIn a business way his word was as\nerood as his bond. He would as\nsoon think of robbing his mother's\nuieuij iika wjiixji nas uuiaruisxieu.\nBut he would'steal the brightest\npossession a woman can have, aud\nmotooiAto f if ,v,.,.,Mo .,V,CT\nj-ji luvnijuiig uiio ixicuuo. I\nrr u ,.:i 1 a\nxxu wuuiu sun ue uuitiauier oi a, I\ngirl too young to be away from her\nmother's care, and cast her adrift\non the storm tossed waters of Bo-\nhernia, without a qualm.\ngrave as ne WOUia OI aeirauamg peuuie to ub iiu nuu serene, s- have seized and levied upon, as the proper\nanybody out of a penny. Finan- sured them that the finances of the \"Sta?\": tiitumbef\nv,; v :uj afa cmA anA six (6) in Block numbered, live (5) in -Bell's\nAnd the honor of young Mr. tion. The average obscure coun\nThaw and wife, too. This is an try newspaper may not have any\nodd institution, also. Mr. Thaw\nhimself, so far as history goes, has\nnot had a worthy aim or a noble\nambition since his birth. He has\nlived for pleasure, has soaked his\nsoul in it until its keen acid has\ndyed it deeply. No doubt, if he in-\ncurred a gambling debt, he would\ndeem it a point of \"honor\" to pay\nit. No doubt he thought it a meas-\nure honor to be able to hold his\nj i ii i 1 1\nend up as long as the rest. As to the\nhonor of his wife let the mantle of\ncharity fall over that toy of base\nmen that has at last caused a trag-\neay\n1 w I\nThey don't know the meaning of\nthe word. Never was a noble a\nphrase in poorer company. Men\nand women of real honor would\nnever have sunk their souls so\ndeeply in the mire of human de-\nPmty as these people have.\nhonor knows them not.\nThe Work of Bij Thieves\nThe Irwin paper company, of\nQuincy, has sent out the. following\ncircular letter to its patrons, among\nwhom is The Blade, touching upon\nthe late money scare\n\"The big financial rascals are\nconvalescing, and now h&t the\ncountry has properly diagnosed\nJ their ailment a plain case of colic\n-apprehension and fear have also\nsubsided.\nOwing to the grimaces, contor-\nturns ana lusty Denowing wmuu\nAMon-manied the first attack, the\nL .i.\nior a moment uiverreu, just as cin-\nUcky infants will throw an entire\nhousehold into confusion; but since\nthe trouble has been located, and\nthfi Tififided carminatives adminis-\nL a u\ntered, business is resuming its won-\noeriui activity.\nAs a matter of fact, the late\npanic if it is entitled to that dig-\nL;,Q irTvir or, 0r.tifl;0i .nr..\n\ndition created by a iew Dig tnieves\nfor the purpose of further plunder-\nmg. cut some way tne piot seems\ntd have been ill-timed, for it is\nhard to convince a person of im\npending disaster or starvation when\nevery outlook presents multiplied\nevidence of prosperity, and when\nwe have just harvested enough\nfarm products to feed a whole hun-\ngry wona. opareribs ana sauer-\nkraut are still important factors in\ndetermining the financial robust-\nness of the country.\nThe only panicky effect notice-\nable in this territory was annoy-\nance occasionally experienced in\nobtaining ready cash, but this has\npractically disappeared.\n'The buying capacity of the peo\nple is not lessened, and, on the\nwhole, the business Outlook seems\nmost reassuring.\n(tt I\nWe congratulate yOU Upon the\nbright prospects Of the new year, And it is further ordered that a copy here\nof be published, according to law. in Thb\nand Wish yOU tne compliments OI Laclkdb Blade, a newspaper published In\nthe season.\"\nWhat the Banks Owe the Newspapers\nIf there is any class of business\nmen in existence who ought to hold\nthe newspaper fraternity in grate\nf nl remembrance, it is the bankers\noi tne country, inuring tne nnan-\ncial crisis the newspapers were the\nsalvation of the country. There\nwas not a firebrand in the whole\nlot. From one end of the country\nto the other in village, town and\ncity the newspapers urged the\ni- j. i- i j i\nvuuuu; \"vn; uj cu ovuuu\nsafe and\nthat the banks were absolutely se-\ncure, and published the utterances\nInf rmfW? finnnmVra fArrnnt nr f rioii-1\n\"f i\nofomta TTa in T\nDuumura. m j.y, l-\neular issued by State Auditor Car-\nroll was published everywhere,\nthus relieving what threatened to\nbecome a most dangerous condi\ncredit at the bank, but he deserves\nall of the bank fraternity. If he is\nprepared to print checks, deposit\nslips, note heads and the like, he\nought to have the privilege of do\ning so, without having to buck a\nlarge lithographic firm in a great\ncity, or a cheap sweat shop in some\nremote town. These outfits are no\nhelp to the banker when the days\nof adversity come. The banks\n3 i a i I I\nneed a lesson in patronizing home\nconcerns as badly as any class of\npeople with whom we are acquaint-\ned. Diagonal Progress.\nMififlrv lnves mnnnv coir a I\nthe philosopher. Yes. and it is I\nThe woman who has a house and\nseveral children to keep clean sel\ndom finds time to hunger for a wid\ner career.\nAs a matter of fact, it isn't so\nmuch what your neighbor thinks of\nt m i v i\nthat counts.\nAn eminent physician declares\nthat two hours of sleep before mid\nnight are worth more than six af-\nter that hour.\n1 Trustee Sale\nWhereas Joseph H. Preston and\nMary Preston,, his wife, by their\ncertain deed of trust dated\nApril 27th, 1903, and recorded in\nthe Recorder's office in and for Linn\ncounty, Missouri, .in Book 151 at\nPoiX,Trlh,n\"S\nnf SapHoti No Four (4) in Town-\nslljp jj0 Fifty-seven (57) North of\nKan ge no. Twenty zvj west, iu\nLinn county, Missouri, to the un\ndersicmed trustee to secure the pro-\nmissory note and debt therein de-\ngcribe(j and debt being\nnow past due and wholly unpaid\nand the said Joseph JUL. rreston\nhaving been dead more than nine\nmouuis, i wm mo v\nlegal holder and owner of such note\nld debt Qn Monday the 10th day\nof February, 1908, at the front door\nof the Postoffice in the City ot La\nclede in Linn county, Missouri, sell\nthe above described land at public\nyendue tQ thfl Mehest bidder for\ncagh in hftnd between tne hour8 Qf\nent o'clock a. m. and five o'clock\np. m. oi said day to satisiy sucn\ndebt and interest as provided by\nthe terms of such trust deed.\n1 1 J A 1.\nHarry J. Libby,\nJan. 11th, 1907. Trustee.\nOrder of Publication\nState of Missouri, County ol Linn, ss.\nIn the Circuit Court. February Term, 1908:\nVIOLA BROWN. Plaintiff.\nJOHN E. BROWN. Pefendant.\nvs.\nORDEK OF PUBLICATION.\nNow at this da v comes the Dlalntiff berein.\nby her attorney, and files her petition and\naffidavit, alleging among other things, that\nripfpndunt,. John E. Brown, is not a resident\nof the state of Missouri and that the ordin\nary process of law can not be served upon\nhim in this state:\nWhereupon, it Is ordered by the clerk In\nvacation, that said defendant be notified by\nDuhlicatlon that Dlalntiff has coiumeuced a\nsuit against him in this court, tbeobjectaud\ngeneral nature of which is to obtain a decree\nof divorce, alimony and maintenance and\nthe custody of plaintiff's uiinoi child, and\nthat unless the satd John E. Brown be and\nappear at this court, at the next term there\nof. lo be begun and holden at the court\nhouse in the Citv of Brookfield.in said couo-\nor before the first day of said term, if the\nterm shall so long continue and if not,then\non or before the last day of said term an-\nf it sin llu 1 7t I. riuv nf fffthpiiapv navt unH nn\nswer or pieau to no ymiuun in emu causo,\ntlw sme will be taKen as confessed, and\nshiu cuuaiy ui xjinn ivr iuur wwhs succes\nsively, published at least once a week. The\nlast insertion to be at least fifteen days be\nfore the first day of said next February\nterm of this court.\nJNO. N. WILSON. Circuit Clerk.\nBy ANN A HALLKNBERG, D. O.\nA true copy from the record.\nWitness mv hand, and seal of-the .Circuit\nCourt of Linn County, this 2-itli day of De\ncember, 1907.\nISEal\nJNO. N. WILSON. Circuit Clerk.\nANNA HAL CENBERG, D. O.\nSheriff's Sale Under Transcript Execution\nBv virtue and authority of a transcript\nexecution Issued from the office of the Clerk\nof the Circuit Court of Linn County, Mo.,\naud to me, the undersigned Sheriff of said\ncounty directed, in favor of H, Black, John\nP. Sallee and Josenta Huffman. co-Dartnera\ndoing business un'der the firm name of\nBlack, Sallee Huffman, and against S. M.\nMcKIsson, aud made returnable to the Feb-\nruary term. mm.\noi said Circuit .uourt. 1\nAflaltion to tne town of Laclede, all lying\nffioM\nof theoir\nween the h.ours 9f nine o'clock in the\niorenoon ana five (o)o clock lu the afternoon\npi tuat aay sen at public vendue to ttie\nhiorhest and best bidder, for cash in hand, in\nKkfleiinn counUty! SK!f LV tS. Sht!\ntitle and interest of the said S. M. McKisson\nof, in and to the above described real es\ntate, to satisfy said execution and costs.\nUKOKUK W.